What is the representative Münchhausen syndrome that appeared in Netflix's The Politicians?
The symptoms are that parents and parents false that healthy children are ill.
The Politicians are broadcast today on Netflix.
The drama is about Patton Hobart, the president of the United States, but the first step is to become the student council president of his high school.
The film was produced by American Horror Story and Gree creator Ryan Murphy, starring Gwinness Partlow, Ben Pratt, and Lucy Bointon.
This is a mental illness where parents behave as if they were physical or mental illness, even though the person under their protection is not really sick.
There are various types of pathologies, including Münchhausen syndrome, which is hypothesized to be a disease of himself.
However, the surrogate Münchhausen syndrome clearly implies that others under their protection are ill.
It is also known as FII or FII, a type of child abuse.
Although it is a rare symptom, parents usually exaggerate or cause symptoms, as if children were sick.
So what are the signs of Münchhausen syndrome?
The symptoms of the disease vary in case-by-case, but NHS points out the following caution.
The child is healthy, but if he is ill, he tries to persuade the medical practitioner.
It can be described as exaggerated or false.
The test results are fabricated to make the child feel sick, such as mixing glucose into the urine sample and showing it to be diabetes.
Excessive medications and other drugs cause symptoms of disease.
How common is the surrogate Münchhausen syndrome?
Since many cases have not been reported, it is difficult to know how widespread this syndrome is.
A study published in 2000 estimated that 89 cases of 100,000 people had occurred in two years.
what should we do if we suspect damage to our children?
Contact local social welfare organizations or call NSPCC Child Protection Helpline 0808 800 5000.
