Pope, warning IT representatives that AI development is based on public interests
On Friday, Pope Francis warned IT representatives, diplomats, investors, and others that the competition for artificial intelligence (AI) development and other digital development would increase social injustice if not accompanied by ethical assessments of public interests.
The Pope said at the Vatican Conference where government diplomats, representatives of Facebook and Google, philosophers, physicists and ethicists met.
At the conference entitled "Public Interest in the Digital Age," a small number of scholars and Catholic bishops were invited.
The three-day conference was the latest evidence of the Vatican's willingness to participate in discussions of future and danger in artificial intelligence development.
At the conference, discussions were held on the future of wartime technology development and increasing machine work, as well as the case studies of gunfire incidents in Christchurch, New Zealand and the responses of social media companies during the atrocities.
In his speech at the conference, the Pope praised the development of technological progress, citing how machines liberated workers from danger and simple labor at the beginning of the Industrial Revolution.
However, he warned that if he relied too much on robotics to pursue profits, he could take away the dignity of labor from humans.
"If technological advancements cause increasingly pronounced inequality, it is not true progress," the Pope warned.
If human so-called technological advances are hostile to public interests, unfortunately, they will go back to a kind of savage state based on the theory of the strong.
According to the organizers of the conference, they want to take advantage of the expertise of the participants in the conference to find people who can become future advisors to the Catholic Church in the high-tech field.
