"My son has no sin.
My daughter and my son."
Barochi's murder has become a major news all over the world, and as a result of neglecting the rules of father-right society, the voices of victims, most women, are rekindled to seek action against the so-called "honorary murder."
Women have been burned, killed, stabbed or strangled by crimes such as choosing their own marriage partner - in Barochi's case, praising their sexuality and embarrassing their family.
The killing is usually done by relatives.
After that, Pakistan's Kisas (murder reward) and Deya (retaliatory) laws allow perpetrators to be pardoned from their relatives.
Three months after Baroch's murder, Congress passed a new bill requiring life imprisonment for honorary murder.
However, it is up to the judge's discretion whether murder is an honorable crime, and the killer can theoretically claim another motive and may be pardoned.
In Baroch's case, his parents initially insisted not give his son a pardon.
However, his parents changed their minds and asked him to forgive him.
With international hatred for murder, the Pakistani government took unprecedented steps to declare the country as a successor with their parents, but the lawsuit continued.
Barochi's famous actions include offering a strip show to the Pakistan Cricket team and wearing a red dress with a wide chest on Valentine's Day.
