According to the UN's Friday announcement, in the last four months, the number of refugees from northwestern Nigeria doubled to about 40,000 due to intensified violence.
According to the United Nations Refugee Agency (UNHCR), a new humanitarian crisis has been created due to this confusion, and by the end of this year, it is necessary to cooperate with each institution to raise funds for $35.5 million.
UNHCR spokesman Barrok said that Boko Haram, an Islamic extremist organization that has been working on anti-government activities in northern Nigeria for ten years, has nothing to do with the recent multiple armed attacks.
Rather, the increased violence in Sokot, Zamfara, and Kazina in Nigeria over the past decade was caused by organized armed groups.
"We look at the horrors of illegal and unstable situations," Barok said on Friday.
The media reported that kidnapping, torture, assault, murder and sexual violence were frequent, and raiders destroyed homes and worked on theft.
Military and police are also sent to fight crime groups in the area.
However, the army was exhausted in battle with Bokoharam and the West African branch of Islamic State, which split from the former organization in 2016.
"The refugees don't come with a group name," says Balok.
What they bring is a terrible experience story.
Most of the refugees pass to neighboring Niger.
UNHCR announced in a statement that the security situation, especially in Sokoto, was deteriorating, and that refugees going to Niger would increase in the coming months.
