Lorraine Kelly: I was told that Glasgow accent would never succeed in the television world.
Lorraine Kelly revealed in his Glasgow accent that he was told by television bosses that he would never succeed.
Before appearing on television for the first time, "I was so nervous," Kelly, 59 years old, said he looked back at 35 years in the broadcasting industry.
"I was 25 years old and I was very nervous," she says.
I worked as an investigator at the BBC Scotland branch, and my boss told me that your Glasgow accent would never succeed in the television industry.
Before I took over the Glasgow office, I went to London to meet everyone on the TV-am team and to see where the show was broadcast.
I never forget Ann Diamond and Mike Morris were interviewing legendary actress Betty Davis that morning.
I couldn't believe I was in the same room as a living legend.
I found out that my favorite place is here.
Kelly began working as a reporter for local newspapers in East Kilbrid, Scotland, and became a reporter for the TV-am Scottish branch in 1984.
In addition, Kelly served as the host of the show on GMTV, ITV's Breckfast and Davelake, and later began a program named Lorraine.
In commemoration of the 35th anniversary, she broadcast a special program that looks back on Kelly's most memorable scenes and interviews.
"Passion and enthusiasm" and "curiosity" were the secret to survival in the television industry, and the host added, "You have to put it into work."
You must be honest and sincere.
Do what you should do, get interested and interested in various people.
Looking back on the news that struck her heart, Kelly revealed that the Dunbrane shooting was "very painful."
The day after the terrible incident that 16 students and teachers were killed, I didn't think many of the families of children who were killed or injured watched us broadcast the show live from Danbourne.
Pam Ross, who was killed by her mother and five-year-old daughter Joanna, personally told me that she wanted to see me, so we talked for hours at her house.
Not taking it all on the show, I went to Joanna's funeral, Pam and I've been friends since.
Kelly also interviewed the couple in 2007 when Kate and Gerry McCann's daughter Madeleine were missing, stating that it was "very hard" and "very respecting the strength and courage of the couple."
The couple must endure the painful and gloomy web of knowing what is happening to their beloved daughter.
The couple is not really sorry.
The 35th anniversary of Lorraine is broadcast on ITV from 8:30 a.m. on Monday, September 30.
Zimbabwe, Chiwenga was afraid of traps.
According to government officials, Vice President Constantino Chiwenga declined the offer of a presidential post from former President Robert Mugabe in the midst of a political change due to fears that it might be a trap to refute military action in November 2017.
During the coup, the Zimbabwe Independent reported last week that Mugabe offered Chiwenga to cede the presidency as negotiations continued between Mugabe and the Defense Forces.
However, the reason why Chiwenga declined the offer was not because of anxiety, but because he saw Mugabe's intention to use Chiwenga to inform the leaders and African Unions around the world that he was stripped of his administration in a coup.
According to a series of tweets by Jamwanda2, which confirmed that officials were senior officials of the Cabinet Office, "Mugabe, who had been in power for 37 years, is willing to cede the government to Chiwenga instead of Emerson Munnagagwa," it is said that intense negotiations were made at that time.
Mugabe, who realized he was losing power, told the government officials that he had made contact with Chiwenga by messengers.
According to government officials, the arbitration between the military headquarters and the late and former presidents was carried out by three persons.
The senior officials said that President Spokesman George Charamba, former deputy head of the Central Intelligence Agency, Aaron Nepera, and Roman Catholic bishop Fidelis Muconoli were involved in the negotiations.
Gideon Gono, the former president of the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe, was one commissioned by Mugabe to deliver the President's seat to the commander of the Zimbabwe Defense Forces Tiwenga alone.
Mugabe, a symbol of Africa after his death than he was alive, attempted to accuse the African Union of military action while seeking intervention by African leaders, but failed.
The offer to cede the presidency to the former CDF (commander of Chiwenga) was not due to the choice of the former president.
"It was an abandoned act to start fatigue in part of the late president's family and to save the dangerously rapidly expanding situation," he wrote.
However, there were a few political aims of the late president, who wanted to change the flow at least diplomatically.
If it were to destroy the constitutional order, it would have been to clash with the African Union's view of the coup, but remember that the commanders had declared that they would not break the constitutional order and would not break it.
The late President, Mugabe, hoped that Chiwenga, the top military officer of the time, would be trapped and destroy the claims of the commanders claiming that he did not break the constitutional order.
The late President Mugabe hoped that the African Union, which had not yet fully grasped the situation, would decide whether it would be a coup, would eventually be called a coup, and that military intervention requests would be considered valid.
That was the intent and calculation underlying this offer.
The authorities say that Mugabe was moving when he realized he was not protected by the defense forces.
He was warned that he would be executed like Kadafi, and Mugabe said he had to write a resignation letter.
The commanders of the military told Mugabe that even if they had invaded the presidential house called Blue Roof, they would not turn guns to the citizens.
At that time, Mugabe said he wanted two things: to protect his family, and to prove his military deprivation.
The commanders and commanders of the time accurately read their intentions.
A strong figurative expression was used in the words of a messenger (gono) telling the president's desperate message: "Is Tiri Bemaqwapa Macwapa (we belong to the camouflage group, the military), we are not politicians or political competition."
The Army told other military commanders in the area that through military officers staying in Zimbabwe, the objective was not to defeat Mugabe but to remove the "criminals" surrounding him.
In order to discuss the coup and successors, Mugabe attempted to bring back Munangagwa, who had been short-term exile in South Africa, using the same method.
In addition to negotiations with the Army, Mugabe needed assistance from the region.
Not only had economic power and regional power, but also because President Jacob Zuma was the chairman of the South African Development Community at the time, South Africans, who were key to this process, refused to intervene, but threatened repeatedly behind it, clarifying that the South African army would be immediately sent to Harare if the military had invaded the presidential residence.
"Just because it was not supported by President Putin and African leaders, it did not come to fruition," the sources tell the Independent.
