China needs strong leadership.
Prior to the 70th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China, the Chinese government stated in a policy document published on Friday.
In a white paper, the State Council of China said that the success of the Communist Party 70 years ago was due to the leadership of the party.
China is vast, and the domestic situation is complicated, but there are few political problems.
Without a unified and powerful leadership, China will face division and collapse, and will be a catastrophe for the world."
The Chinese authorities have long justified dealing with problems in a rigid manner, such as the suppression of the democratic movement in Beijing in 1989 as necessary for national stability.
On Tuesday, President Xi Jinping, who plays the leading role in the commemoration ceremony of the world's second largest economic power, has strengthened the party's control since he took power in late 2012.
Xi also oversaw the modernization program of the military that threatened the area.
The policy document states that China does not intend to export its own development models, nor does it intend to incorporate models of other countries, but rather merely seek peace.
Among the genes of Chinese people, there is no invasion or world control of other people.
In modern times, China was bullied by the powerful, and war and confusion left a deep scar with its pain; China would never take the pain he experienced to others.
China is facing difficult issues such as economic stagnation and anti-government movements in Chinese Hong Kong.
The White Paper states that China will never "abandon" its core interests and will not allow its security and sovereignty to be undermined.
"The threat of trade wars and rising tariffs are no problem-solving," the White Paper states in relation to trade disputes with Washington.
China is a mature economic nation with the momentum of complete industrial systems, complete industrial chains, wide market space and strong economic development.
"It will never weaken in the trade war," White said.
I am convinced that China is capable of facing difficulties, turning crisis into opportunities and opening a new world.
China has no idea of countering the U.S. and does not want to replace the U.S., so the U.S. should take the development of China calmly.
The United States cannot control China, and it is even more unlikely to stop China's development.
The U.S. will not maintain its strength if it suppresses, suppresses, and moves domestic contradictions abroad.
