Same-sex marriage justice judgment The opportunity to broaden diversity: Hokkaido Shimbun
The Utsunomiya District Court's Maoka Branch made a decision to approve the case in which 'in fact marriage (internal marriage) ' that conforms to marriage was established even between same sex.
There are more than 20 countries in which same-sex marriage is allowed, and even within Japan, municipalities such as Sapporo City have a system to certify same-sex partnerships.
The court ruled that the two women were actually married.
It is considered the first judicial decision to recognize legal protection by same-sex couples and is meaningful.
The same-sex marriage is not permitted due to the provisions of civil law and family register law.
I would like to deepen my understanding of the rights and security of sexual minorities and discuss the legal system to recognize diverse families.
The women lived together for about seven years and obtained a marriage certificate in the United States.
The court ruled that "the reality of marriage between men and women is not the same" based on the results of living together.
It is a revolutionary decision to extend the recognition of actual marriage with the same-sex rights, such as social insurance.
What is more important is the interpretation of Article 24 of the Constitution of "freedom of marriage" as marriage "only based on the agreement of both sexes."
Both sexes were "unpresumed to be same-sex marriage at the time of establishment, so it is not understood to be the purpose of denying same-sex marriage."
While the Constitution does not assume same-sex marriage, it is expected that it will be a driving force for same-sex marriage lawsuits in various regions.
On the other hand, due to the absence of same-sex marriage, the problem remained that the amount of compensation was reduced as "the benefits of legal protection differ from that of men and women."
It may be difficult to distinguish the right to protect, while recognizing the same reality as men and women.
According to a nationwide survey of domestic trends for married women, about 70 percent of people believe that same-sex marriage should be recognized by law.
As lifestyle diversification progresses, if law is bound by traditional family images, it will take away the rights of those who do not fit it.
In fact, marriage is not a legal spouse, so there are still few restrictions, such as not receiving preferential treatment in the tax system and not having joint custody.
In consideration of same-sex marriage, it is necessary to review family legislation from a variety of perspectives, including not only same-sex marriage but also expanding legal rights for actual marriage.
