[Published on September 27]
the serious pollution of popular tourist destinations
Among Sydney's tourism resources that bring $209 million to the Australian economy every year, Sydney Harbour is the largest employer with opera houses, Circler Keys, Luna Park and some famous Harbour Bridge.
But under the bridge there is an ugly truth.
Sydney's famous port is one of Australia's worst waterways, with about 15 cups of contaminants in the Olympic pool each year.
Thanks to this terrible statistics, one of our biggest tourist attractions is one of the dirtyest places.
According to a new video titled "From Sydney Harbour to Down," the waterways around Australia's most popular cities are filled with shells, plastic bags and plastic bottles, shoes and clothes that someone has lost, and even animal corpses - all flowing rainwater into Sydney Harbour.
Among them, plastic is the biggest factor in clotting waterways.
In a video that was accidentally released on September 27, the day of world tourism, Dr. Katherine Dafoon, vice president of the Sydney Harbour Research Program, said, "This is paradox."
Although its appearance is certainly beautiful, it is one of the most polluted estuary of Japan's coastline.
According to CSIRO, 1560 kilograms of plastic per hour is expected to flow into the waterway, most of which flow through rainwater drainage into Sydney Harbour.
"The heavy rain fell several times, but Sydney Harbour was... quite tragic," Dr. Daffon said.
Two-thirds of the pollution comes from rainwater flowing through the road surface.
However, under the surface of Sydney Harbour, 70 percent of the plastics that flow into the ocean are deposited in the seabed.
"If you really don't go down the sea level, you don't know the truth about what's there," said the owner Richard Nichols, Dive Center Manley, who collects about 500 kilograms of plastic waste each year by himself and his team.
If a lot of people know more (what's under the water), I think everyone will be really surprised.
Although overwhelming, more than half of the items we discover are plastic bags.
The other half is plastic at least somewhere.
Sydney Harbour is beautiful at first glance, and no one can believe that all of these plastics and garbage are flowing right under the water.
Jeremy Brown, one of the founders and director of Ocean Protect, said that local residents and tourists may be able to reduce plastic and garbage flowing into the waterways.
he says, we should start from the source.
It reduces the amount of plastic used, recycles better, and eventually flows into the sea, so you have to focus more on what is flowing into the drain.
50 percent of the oxygen we breathe comes from the ocean, so hurting the ocean will kill us.
The oceans absorb 30% of carbon dioxide and are food sources.
But we can restore Sydney Harbour and return it to its old form, but it is very simple.
killing the sea means killing people.
A new study on plastics and mental health was also presented this month, coincided with the release of the video funded by the recycling company TOMRA, as part of a broader awareness of environmental protection and the reduction of the impact of beverage containers that remain in the natural environment.
According to a new study, 82 percent of 546 children between the ages of 12 and 18 have a feeling of despair about plastic waste, and 25 percent think that disposable plastic waste is an adult's fault.
The study also stated that 93 percent of 551 parents surveyed were increasingly worried about the amount of plastic waste flowing into the ocean.
Most of the participants said they wanted to do something about plastic waste, but they didn't know how to change it, which led to ecological anxiety.
The former Karatsu Power Station was demolished in October | Saga News | Saga News
The chimney of the former Karatsu Power Station, which began demolition work in October, is Futatako, Karatsu City.
Kyushu Electric Power Co., Ltd. announced on October 26 that it would begin dismantling the chimney of the former Karatsu Power Station (oil-fired power plant) located in Futatako, Karatsu City.
Construction will be completed by the end of March 2021.
The two cars were used to discharge gas during power generation, with a height of about 180 meters.
The original three were removed in 1991 due to aging.
One of the chimneys is broken down by a tower crane.
The plan takes nine months for each decomposition and takes 18 months.
The remaining turbine buildings and boilers have not been demolished.
The man in his 60s, who runs a restaurant nearby, said, "When I look at the chimney from the distance, it is like a symbol that made me feel back to Karatsu.
The former Karatsu Power Station began operation in 1967, and the first was abolished in 89 and the second was abolished in 2015.
It is located in the corner of Karatsu Higashi Port and has an area of about 225 thousand square meters.
Due to the proximity of Yacht Harbor and JR Nishi Karatsu Station, the prefecture and the city want to use the site.
Three of them, including nine electric cars, signed an agreement on the use of the site in 15 years.
