The World Rally Championship will be held in Japan in November 2020.
It is the first of its kind to be held in New York City - Yahoo!
The World Rally Championship will be held in Japan in November 2020
The FIA announced on September 27, 2019 that the FIA World Rally Championship will be held in Aichi Prefecture and Gifu Prefecture on November 22, 2020.
Look back at past WRC World Rally Championship with images!
18 cards.
The last event in Japan was held in Hokkaido in 2010.
What is the WRC that will be revived in 2020.
The WRC World Rally Championship (WRC) is one of the four World Championships in which the International Automobile Federation (FIA) manages, along with Formula One (F1) and the World Endurance Championship.
Since 1973, it has become the world's highest rally championship with a history and tradition held every year, and it is said that the competition is the toughest car competition because it runs not only on closed roads (paved roads), but also on various roads such as gravel and snow roads at high speed.
In the 2018 season, Toyota won the WRC Manufacturing Challenger title for the second season since 1999.
This time, the Japan Round Preparation Committee was established to host the event in Japan.
As a result, it was decided that the 2020 WRC Japan Round will be held at the World Motorsport Council, the highest voting body of the International Automobile Federation.
Mr. Akio Toyoda (President and CEO of Toyota Motor Corporation), the governor of Aichi Prefecture and Gifu Prefecture, and the general representative of TOYOTA GAZOO Racing WRT, said the following.
Governor of Aichi Prefecture Hideaki Omura
"We sincerely welcome the FIA World Rally Championship to be held in Japan in 2020, and we will work with relevant parties to ensure that the FIA World Rally Championship will be held in Japan in the fall of 2020.
Hajime Furuta, Governor of Gifu Prefecture
"I am very pleased that the Japanese round of the FIA World Rally Championship will be held here in 2020, where the Tokyo Olympic and Paralympic Games will be held.This is the first global motor sports tournament for the prefecture, and I am looking forward to seeing you all at this moment."
Mr. Akio Toyoda (President and CEO of Toyota Motor Co., Ltd.)
"I am very happy to run Yaris WRC in Japan.
Thank you for your support."
Mr. Keiji Furuya, Chairman of the Association for Promotion of Motor Sports, commented on the Japanese round.
The Japan round of the WRC World Rally Championship will be held from 19 to 22 November 2020.
The area is a public road in Aichi Prefecture (Nagoya, Okazaki City, Toyota City, Shinjo City, Nagakute City and Shitara Town) and in Gifu Prefecture (Nakatsugawa City and Ena City).
The main venue is "Love - Global Expo Memorial Park" which was opened on the site of the 2005 Japan International Exposition.
The Japan Round Invitation Preparatory Committee will hold a decision-making meeting at the Tokyo Motor Show 2019 venue, and the Central Rally Aichi/Gifu 2019 test event will be held on November 9 and 10, 2019.
is Tasmanian devil the key to cancer treatment?
Tasmanian devils may be the key to cancer treatment - researchers have opened a breakthrough that could lead to major reforms in patient care.
Medical researchers found out how some cancer cells camouflaged.
Researchers have found that the same process occurs in Tasmanian devils and humans.
It is expected that this discovery will create a new method for treating cancer patients.
What is the commonality between Tasmanian devils and humans?
It is an invisible cancer cell.
A team of researchers, including researchers at the Peter McCallum Cancer Center in Melbourne, found that cancers that do not respond to immunotherapy could significantly alter their treatments for cancer.
It may be the key to addressing lethal face tumors that threaten the future of Tasmanian devils near extinction.
The study found that some cancer cells in humans and alkalis use a series of proteins called PRC2 to camflageate, causing markers to no longer react and the immune system to no longer attack cancer.
This is a major challenge for treating a type of skin cancer called small cell lung cancer, neuroblastoma and Merkel cells.
Peter McCallum researcher Mark Dawson said, "The very important thing in this project is that we may be able to reverse the process for patients who are resistant to immunotherapy."
Traditional treatments may be reused to revitalize markers, or proteins known as MHCs, and immune systems may be able to identify cancer cells.
"It may have a significant impact on lung cancer patients," Dawson said.
"Lung cancer is a disease prevalent in the world.
And it could be treated in a much better way.
Researchers expect this discovery to eventually be used to treat Tasmanian devil's face-to-face tumors, where cancer cells escape detection as well.
"Unsurprisingly, exactly the same process occurs in humans and Tasmanian devils," Professor Dawson said.
"It was very difficult to treat tumors in Tasmanian devils.
However, if drugs that are effective in humans can be used in Tasmanian devils, it may help control tumors."
scientists are puzzled by giant planets orbiting tiny stars.
Scientists are surprised by the discovery of a solar system that covers the current understanding of planetary formation, where giant Jupiter-type planets orbit around a small star called red dwarf, 30 light years away from Earth.
On September 26, 2019, an artistic image of the giant gas giant GJ3512b orbiting its main star, the red dwarf was released.
Stars are usually much larger than the largest planets orbiting around them.
In this case, however, the magnitude of stars and planets is not much different, the researchers said on Thursday.
The star, called GJ3512, is about 12 percent the size of the Sun, but the planet orbiting around it has at least half the mass of Jupiter, the largest planet in our solar system.
Juan Carlos Morales, astrophysicist at the Catalan Institute of Space Studies at the Spanish Institute of Space Sciences, led this research published in the journal Science.
The theoretical model of formation shows that normally low-mass stars are the main stars of small planets similar to Earth and small Neptune, so this discovery was surprising.
In this case, we discovered a giant gas planet similar to Jupiter around a very small star."
The planet, composed mainly of gas, like Jupiter, was discovered using a telescope at the Calalto Observatory in Spain.
The planet orbits around the star for 204 days.
The red dwarf is small and the surface temperature is relatively low.
The GJ3512 is not only much smaller than our Sun, but also about the same size as the giant planet, about 35 percent larger than Jupiter.
Because the emission energy is small, it is darker than the Sun, and the surface temperature is quite low as about 3800 degrees Celsius (6380 degrees Celsius/3527 degrees Celsius).
That's why I have a red color."
While there is a sign that the second planet is currently orbiting the star, Morales said that the third planet may have been released from its stellar system in the past, explaining its elliptical orbit.
Planets are produced from the same disk, consisting of interstellar gas and dust that produced the star that orbits itself.
In the most powerful planetary formation model called the "core accumulation" model, the object is formed from solid particles in the disk, and the gravity produced by the egg of the planet causes the surrounding gas to become atmospheric.
This unusual planetary system may be explained using a conflict model called a self-gravity instability model.
"In this case, the protoplanetary disk surrounding the newly born star may have been slightly larger and less hot than was thought," Morales said.
Since the disk becomes unstable in this state, some dense regions may also appear.
These masses can grow until they collapse and form planets.
