Alfa Laval, 10 million Swedish krona natural gas projects
Alfa Laval, one of the world's leading heat exchangers, centrifugal separation and water treatment companies, received an order to provide air cooling equipment to a natural gas treatment plant in the United States.The project is about 100 million Swedish krona, and the energy sector's welding heat exchanger division is working, but deliveries are scheduled for 2020.
The project includes the Alfa Laval Niagara air cooling system, which will be used as part of a cooling system to separate natural gas from individual pure materials - ethane, propane and bethane.
Safety is important in all industrial processes, but careful natural gas processing is critical.
"Our reliable air cooling equipment is rated for safety performance that customers can feel at ease," said Suzanne Paren Okrund, Head of Energy.
As you know, ethane, propane, and bethane are separated from natural gas, and can then be used as raw materials for petrochemical plants and household heaters, or as fuel for vehicles.
about alpha laval
Alpha Laval is the world's leading supplier of special products and engineering solutions based on its main technology, heat exchange, separation and water treatment.
Alpha Laval's facilities, systems and services are designed to help customers optimize their manufacturing processes.
The solution helps customers heat, cool, separate and transport products in the food and beverage, chemical, petrochemical, pharmaceutical, starch, sugar and ethanol manufacturing industries.
Alpha Laval's products are used in power plants, ships, oil and natural gas exploration, mechanical engineering, and mining, as well as in wastewater treatment, air conditioning and refrigerator applications.
Alpha-Laval organizations around the world work with customers from around 100 countries to help customers lead the international community.
Alfa Laval is a listed company in Nasdaq OMX, with annual sales of approximately 4.7 billion Swedish krona (about €40 billion) in 2018.
The number of employees was about 17200.
5 Medical Institutions in Saga Prefecture | Administrative and Social News|Saga Shimbun
The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (MHLW) announced the hospital's name on September 26 as a need for reorganization and integration.
Of the 13 medical institutions surveyed in the prefecture, 38 and 5% are the 10th highest in Japan, and three have already been integrated and relocated.
The hospital is named after the National Hospital Organization Higashi-Saga Hospital (Miyaki-cho, Miyoki-gun), Takyu City Hospital (Takyu City), Kojo Municipal Hospital (Kojo City), Imari Matsuura Hospital (Imari City), Regional Medical Function Promotion Organization (Imari City), and Tatara Hospital in Taramachi, Fujitsu County.
Of these, Takyu City Hospital and Kojo Municipal Hospital are planning to build a new hospital in Higashi Takyu-cho, Takyu City, and Imari Matsuura Hospital has been relocated to Matsuura City, Nagasaki Prefecture.
Taira Hospital is the center of community comprehensive care in the town, and has been operating surplus in recent years.
Mayor Takayuki Nagabuchi stressed that "the town has the idea of operating alone and cooperating with neighboring city hospitals, and the hospital must remain absolutely for the residents," and expressed negative views on reorganization and integration.
The administrative director of the Higashi-Saga Hospital said, "We do not hear the contents from the prefecture," and concluded that "We will actively participate in the prefectural regional medical planning coordination conference and respond to it based on the purpose of the discussion."
The Organization for Promotion of Regional Medical Functions (Tokyo), which operates Imari Matsuura Hospital, said, "The announcement is not a mechanical decision to determine the direction of public hospitals, but rather a request to review them again at regional medical planning coordination meetings in each prefecture."
"We would like to hear from the parties about the future operation of the hospital.
In some cases, it may be necessary to review medical subjects and to further reduce the beds."
