How do you taste honey collected by Flying Bees bred at the foot of Flying B?
In May 2019, honey was harvested for the first time in September 2019.
More than 100 honey bees were collected from only two nest boxes.
Why did Bentley make bees on the grounds of a factory that assembled cars?
I want to taste this!
The honey produced by Bentley is here (11 sheets)
Peter Bosch, executive officer in the manufacturing department of Bentley, commented as follows.
"In order to contribute to the conservation of biodiversity in the region, we established a nest box for the first time in the vast grounds of the Crew Plant at the beginning of this year.
The beekeepers have been watching the bees from the wildflowers planted on the site and the surrounding mountains collecting nectar from various flowers.
It turns out that this place is suitable for beekeeping, and it is wonderful to have such a harvest in the first year.
Bentley is engaged in a wide range of activities through its Crew Plant and our business to become the top sustainable luxury car manufacturers, and is also part of this effort.
Staff are actively cooperating.
It is very pleased that the first harvest was successfully received, and we plan to install more nest boxes next year to increase the yield of bentree honey.
A small step will lead to the conservation of biodiversity in the region.
We will continue to carry out various initiatives to fulfill our role."In May 2019, 1.2 million honeybees, Flying Bees, were launched.
In September of the same year, a summer passed, the work of removing the nest frame from the nest box was completed, and the nest frame was put on a centrifugal separator, and after filtering the fallen honey, it was bottled.
The bottle and package of honey can also be seen with Bentley-like commitment.
The design of the label was handled by Louise McCallum, the designer responsible for the interior of Bentley.
The bottled honey is not only distributed to staff but also given to important customers and guests who visit the crew factory.
The UK is a country that values tea time.
In addition to fennel tea that is compatible with honey, we would like to enjoy afternoon tea together with " Flying Bees" honey in scones and other places.
