In fiscal 2018, 90% of companies applied for recruitment, while the percentage of companies that were able to secure the number of appointments was around 50% for new graduates and mid-career regular employees, and only 30% for non-regular employees.
Many companies responded with "approval" to raise the yen to 1,000 yen per hour, including information-related (100 percent), construction (70,6%), and wholesale (61,7%).
The majority of respondents were manufacturers (51 and 9 percent) and service businesses (60 and 9 percent) including food, drink, and lodging.
The representative of the conference said, "Although there is a tendency to be a high percentage of opposition in industries with high part-time and hourly wages, there are many companies that think it is difficult to secure human resources and that it is likely to increase labor costs."
The average salary of the companies who answered "the opposite" was 895 yen (from October 4, Fukui Prefecture was 829 yen).
