the white house, a panic without impeachment.
On Thursday, the White House officials were excited to counter the impeachment pressure of the new Democratic Party, and detailed officials explained that this week there was a "great panic" feeling against the lack of plans to address the emerging reality.
A person close to the White House said that the atmosphere of the West Wing seems to be increasing "confidents, anxiety, and worry" about the possibility that the appeal of whistleblowers would damage the President and some surrounding persons.
He said, "I don't really think it's true."
The White House official joked that there were no obvious plans for the situation, or that the usual measures that the President had made to deal with the matter so far could not be applied, so there was no confidence in how to proceed, as this claim was so serious that it would not seem to be erased from the next news.
Another person familiar with the controversy described the atmosphere in the White House as "a state of great shock" as the President's uncontrollable response to the impeachment question would increase the likelihood of "uncontrollable."
Another source of concern is that during the impeachment interrogation, the pressure of the president is seen to be raised every day, and some of the close associates of the president are expected to further "impulsive" behavior.
Trump has spurred concerns about the increasingly unpredictable actions and the possibility of violent attacks by unexpected means, and has been concerned about the president and politics in the electoral year.
Trump faced the greatest threat he had ever faced during his term of office, and has changed his hands, becoming an attacker, becoming a defense, and reviving the strategy he considered effective during the Russian investigation of Robert Moller.
Trump tried to neglect the request of the Ukrainian president to cooperate in the investigation of political opponents, disinterested in the activities of the Democratic Party and President Joe Biden, and attempted to undermine the credibility of the whistleblower as a motive for partisan conflict.
However, many of the White House officials have endured the Mora trials, but this time they are beginning to feel the difference.
The president, whose powers are branded, seemed to be coming to the press conference on Wednesday, said a person familiar with this situation.
Trump enjoyed asking questions about Russia's alleged investigation, but did not seem to have answered questions about Ukraine.
Some of the whistleblowers are convinced that damage can be mitigated, claiming that it is a fact that it undermines the credibility of the whistleblowers, as some are aware of the fact that they did not have direct information about the calls with President Trump, Vladimir Zerensky, and Ukrainian Presidents, which are controversial.
Furthermore, it often happens when the president is attacked, but the momentum of support increases to defend against such facts.
However, a Republican strategic family close to the White House points out that the president's basic support rate is already very high and the impeachment will not have much effect on gaining new supporters.
In particular, if impeachment interferes with the legislative agenda and monopolizes the news during the forty-six o'clock period, "there is no advantage to focus on impeachment by the President for the next four months."
Another source stated that those claiming impeachment could be the help of the president did not fully understand how uncertain the president's response would be.
Concerned White House officials seek advice from their advisors to organize impeachment teams.
According to an official who explained this plan, the initiative is still in its early stages, but it is still unclear what kind of initiatives such as the Strategic Decision Office will be implemented and what kind of actions will be implemented.
However, he said that there is a recognition that a clear leader who can organize public relations activities aggressively is needed to counter organizational legal strategies and communication strategies, and the publication and publication of critical internal accusations against the momentum of Democratic impeachment.
For more information on this situation, the lack of a long-term strategic perspective is clearly visible, as Secretary of State Mike Pompeo and Secretary of Finance Steven Munusin stated that they would not publish a note on Trump's call with the Ukrainian president 48 hours later.
It is expected that more pressure will be raised now than Robert Morler's investigation, which he said only through almost inconsistent indictments.According to the person involved, the person who may be involved in the impeachment deployment is called Trump's external pitbull, and Corrie Luwandowski, who served as the head of the former electoral ward.
However, Luwandowski told NBC News that it is not accurate to suggest that he would be the leader of such efforts.
"We've been doing everything we can to support the president and policy for the past five years, but we've never talked to the president or his close associates about participating in a team that counters this impeachment."
Trump's external attorney, Jay Clow, is also involved in impeachment.
In an interview with NBC News, Clow said, "The problem is handled properly."
Emmett Frad, who was engaged in Clinton's impeachment and led the White House until the end of the Moller investigation, left Pat Cipolon, the current White House legal adviser, with little experience, and the White House now lacks lawyers with experience in impeachment.
