The possibility of emission reduction in renewable biofuel research
In recent years, although electric vehicles, Tesla trucks and semis have monopolized the news, they are the only ones flying in the air that can not reach renewable energy.
However, the University of Alberta has developed a technology to make renewable biofuels available as jet fuel.
Dr. David Bresler, Professor of Agriculture, Life and Environmental Sciences, Alberta, launched the project in 2003.
Professor's laboratory develops hydrocarbon fuel from lipid waste such as oil and fat from restaurants, livestock rendering, and canola oil.
Unlike ethanol and other biofuels, this technology uses low-quality fats for production, 85% less carbon emissions than crude oil-based fuels, and other industrial wastes during production.
This technology also contributes to the reproduction of hydrocarbons in crude oil-based fuels.
Dr. Bresler said that the technology achieved (actually generated) in the first generation was hydrocarbons of the molecules themselves in diesel gasoline.
Although it is a new option to use biofuels, conventional biofuel technologies tend to destabilize at low temperatures, causing serious problems for aircraft moving high altitudes.
"The jet fuel problem is something like a dilemma," Bresler said.
It is not as valuable as diesel, but it has higher requirements.
Dr. Bresler's laboratory currently focuses on two options for jet biofuels.
The first is a low-risk approach that requires another treatment of hydrocarbon biofuels to add hydrogen.
The second option is to continue researching chemical reactions that are already partially developed to maintain fuel stability even at low temperatures.
Dr. Bresler described the second option as "can be tested with a reactor to change the chemical reaction slightly."
This option is risky.
With airlines, Canada and the U.S. Army increasing investment in renewable options, Forge Hydrocarbons, a subsidiary of Alberta University, is working on commercialization.
"They predict that someday someone will impose carbon taxes in the future," he said.
I want to prepare the worst case alternative.
Currently, Foge operates a testing plant near Edmonton's Waste Management Center, and recently invested $4 million from Lockheed Martin to help build a 25 million US production facility in Sonbra, Ontario.
The plant will produce about 19 million liters of biofuel annually.
Dr. Bresler argues that carbon reduction is about 85%, but the reduction rate does not increase in fuel transport and production.
"As a technologist," Bresler says.
My job is to create an option so that multiple options can be made in parallel with the above-mentioned decisions.
