exposure to a large amount of pesticides can increase the risk of heart disease and heart attack
Current studies have shown that working around high-concentration pesticides may increase the risk of heart disease later.
This was the result of a more than 30 years of follow-up survey of Japanese Americans living in Hawaii.
Researchers found that the risk of heart disease and heart attack increased by 45 percent compared to men who did not work around pesticides.
"This research highlights the importance of wearing personal protective gear when exposed to pesticides at work, describing the presence of pesticide exposure at work in medical records, and reducing the standard risk factors of heart disease," says Dr. Beatrice Rodriguez, co-author of the study.
Dr. Rodriguez is a professor of the Department of Elderly Care at the University of Hawaii in Manoa.
This is the result of research on data collected from more than 6,000 men living on Oahu Island who participated in the Kuakini Honolulu Heart Program.
Researchers have stated that this study may not be applied to women or other races, as only Japanese-American men are concerned.
Due to the long half-life of pesticides, health effects may appear years after exposure.
The study had the greatest impact within 10 years of exposure.
"As a result of a 34-year follow-up study, the relationship between exposure of pesticides in work and heart disease and heart attack is no longer important," Dr. Rodriguez said in a press release.
This is probably due to the increased importance of other factors related to aging and the possible relationship between pesticides and heart disease in later years.
The researchers found that exposure to low and moderate pesticides was not important to heart disease and heart attack.
