Ghana won two awards at the International Civil Aviation Organization
Ghana won two prestigious awards at the 40th International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) General Assembly in Montreal, Canada.
The award was awarded to Ghana for provisional implementation of 89.89% and the highest score in Africa for air safety supervision.
Prior to this, ICAO completed its coordinated verification survey (ICVM) on 3 April 2019 in accordance with the United Nations Aviation Organization's World Safety Audit Report.
The safety award was recognized by Ghana to comply with the standards and agreements recommended by ICAO on safety at airports and national airspace.
These awards were created as part of the ICAO's delayed national zero campaign support.
In addition, 16 certifications for safety evaluation and 17 certifications for security evaluation were awarded to ICAO participating countries with improved safety standards.
The award was awarded to Joseph Kofi Ada, Minister of Aviation of Ghana, Simon Alati, Director General of Civil Aviation of Ghana, Nii Icoi Otou, Ambassador of Ghana to Canada, and Yau Kuwakwa, Director of Ghana Airport Company.
In his speech, President Olmiwa Bennard Aliou stressed the need to maintain aviation safety in participating countries.
"It is important to continue to be aware that aviation safety, security, and sustainability are still the most fundamental priorities in this era of innovation."
Mr. Ada said the award was a gift of Ghana's efforts to complement the sector's indomitable efforts and perseverance.
He further pointed out that the aviation industry has a tremendous potential to develop the domestic economy as "air is likely to dramatically change our lives."
There are social and economic benefits, but all of them are safe and secure that we have achieved.
