List of lost dresses by Elizabeth I in Hampton Court Palace
It was made of the finest Camlet silk, woven with silver foil yarn, and the luxurious embroidery of plants, animals and butterflies was fluffy.
Elery Lynn, the dress collection curator at the Historic Royal Palace, is determined to be one.
Lin saw this faded piece of cloth on the wall of a small church in one rural area, which was placed 100 years ago, and is considered to be part of the clothing lost from Elizabeth's clothing dance.
Three years after Lynn accidentally found this luxurious cloth, which was used as an altarpiece for the church in Baxton, Helefordshire, Elizabeth's lost dress will be displayed next month at Hampton Court Palace near exactly the room where the Tudor Queen could have worn over 450 years ago.
The only remaining dress in the 16th century was a single one, which proved to be an important discovery throughout the Royal Dress Collection.
Although there is no perfect evidence that Elizabeth passed the sleeves to the dress, three years of research raised the conviction of experts that the dress was not part of the royal possession.
The exquisitely expensive textile "cloth made of silver thread" was provided by law only to senior members of the royal family, but the embroidery of plants and flowers of the "name" quality also suggests that the later additions of deer, dogs, butterflies, fishermen and bears were noble figures.
It is believed that the dress was equivalent to a Tudor mansion when it was made.
Furthermore, in the 1590s at the end of the Elizabethan period, it is speculated that the Queen was increasingly threatened by other women in the palace and could not stand up against rivalries wearing such luxury clothing.
Lin said that it was important to publish it, so he came to see his colleagues.
I was always very happy to see the cloth and say, "It's amazing," and I was convinced that I was watching one of the royal dresses."
A long second life of a piece of dress used as an altarpiece of the unmarked Baxton Church of St. Faith seems unexpected but not so much.
Baxton is a village from Blanche Parley, who served as a court lady throughout Queen Elizabeth's long life.
The dress dates back to 1590 when Paley died, but experts believe it must have been presented to the family or church as a memorial to Paley before Elizabeth died in 1603.
Over 1,000 hours of repair, of which 400 hours of specially dyed silk and thin surgical needles were spent on very delicate sewing, will be displayed next to the rainbow portrait depicting Elizabeth wearing a similar dress, one of the most admired contemporary paintings borrowed from Hatfield House during the exhibition.
The space as wide as possible to store some of the very expensive tapestries is only a renovated greenhouse on the Hampton Court grounds, where most of the preservation work was done and led by Libby Thompson, who said, "If you're dealing with historical fabrics, you're really impressed by the craftsmanship of those who made it."
When you look at the embroidered on the front and back, you will find a very big respect for the person who made this.
I have never seen such sophisticated works before.
Elizabeth's lost dress exhibition will be held at Hampton Court Palace from October 12.
